<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1436,152,978]" box="[198,1423,872,898]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis box="[198,330,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Old English 
<emphasis box="[606,696,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">twegen,</emphasis>
meaning “two,” in reference to the pair of tergal maculations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis box="[198,301,912,937]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is known only from the female. It is distinguished by its size, the two yellow maculae on tergum II, and the contrasting silver and black setae.
</paragraph>
